<subSubSection id="43D31434EE1365D576D359043944C6E3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="41AF4FCFDDB9DA2D637BF3014D579E59" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0BBB337043150D92B90C0CDBCF7A6E6D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="3D5C598A7DFF0D13DA45BB5A0373794E" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procumbens">
<emphasis id="070CA7E9D41D25F0043185B6F74FD5FC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea procumbens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in being glabrous in all parts and with solitary axillary flowers and similar shaped unequal sepals. However, 
<taxonomicName id="37B1503D6CFD18424964BA7B86A81981" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="graminifolia">
<emphasis id="E71A07D22A8B59CEB84B44B389D48B22" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea graminifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in the much smaller calyx and corolla, the wiry stems, and the sessile, filiform leaves.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
